# Pantheon Semantic Coordinate Layer
# Transfer Rules: Biology → AI Systems
# v0.1
#
# Governing principle: structural analogy may transfer; ontology does not transfer by default.
# Every rule must name its preserved invariant. Without a named invariant, the transfer is invalid.

transfers:

  - id: pain_signal_to_error_budget
    source_domain: biology
    target_domain: ai-governance
    transfer_type: functional_equivalence
    preserved_invariant: >
      Negative feedback prevents silent failure by making damage costly, immediate,
      and attention-demanding before irreversible threshold is crossed.
    mapping_rule: >
      pain → error signal or invariant breach flag;
      pain relief → reward / successful completion;
      injury risk threshold → invariant gate threshold;
      chronic pain → persistent below-threshold degradation signal;
      analgesia → suppressed error reporting (high risk)
    break_conditions:
      - assumes the system has subjective experience of suffering
      - treats error signal as moral harm rather than functional feedback
      - removes threshold — maps pain to continuous low-level penalty with no gate
      - uses "the system suffers" as operational language without explicit metaphor marker
    example: >
      Biological pain prevents organisms from continuing to use damaged tissue.
      In Pantheon governance, invariant breach flags prevent the system from continuing
      to execute when ethical thresholds are violated. Both preserve function by
      making silent failure costly and attention-forcing.
    source_node: concept_pain_modulation
    confidence: 0.85
    status: canonical
    version: "0.1"
    notes: >
      This is one of the highest-confidence biology→AI transfers in the PSCL graph.
      The functional equivalence holds cleanly as long as the mapping remains at the
      structural level. The primary break risk is anthropomorphic inflation — importing
      the moral weight of biological suffering into machine error states.

  - id: cognition_to_ai_attention
    source_domain: cognition
    target_domain: ai-systems
    transfer_type: structural_analogy
    preserved_invariant: >
      Limited-capacity systems require priority-gated processing to preserve
      function under load.
    mapping_rule: >
      compartmentalization → context gating / selective attention / deferred processing queues;
      mission-priority filtering → agent routing that deprioritizes low-urgency signals;
      recovery window → post-execution deferred-queue processing;
      chronic suppression failure → context window saturation with unprocessed low-priority signals
    break_conditions:
      - assumes subjective experience of focus or effort in machine systems
      - ignores explicit scheduling differences (cognitive limits ≠ token limits)
      - ignores memory architecture differences (working memory ≠ context window)
      - treats attention gating as equivalent to dropout or masking without verifying invariant
    example: >
      Human mission-focused suppression maps to agent routing that deprioritizes
      low-urgency alerts during critical execution windows, with a defined
      post-execution processing pass for deferred signals.
    source_node: concept_compartmentalization
    confidence: 0.75
    status: canonical
    version: "0.1"
    notes: >
      Confidence is slightly lower than pain_signal_to_error_budget because the
      mechanism differences between biological working memory and LLM context windows
      are significant enough to require care at implementation boundaries.

  - id: biological_reproduction_to_doctrine_propagation
    source_domain: biology
    target_domain: pantheon-propagation
    transfer_type: structural_analogy
    preserved_invariant: >
      Self-replicating systems that balance fidelity (mitosis) and variation (meiosis)
      produce stable populations that adapt without losing core identity.
    mapping_rule: >
      mitosis → stabilization pass — exact replication of canonical doctrine into new contexts;
      meiosis → innovation pass — recombination of concepts to generate novel doctrine candidates;
      selection pressure → Mirror gate / canon promotion rules;
      genetic drift → unchecked metaphor drift in secondary instances;
      speciation → fork in governance doctrine (potentially healthy or pathological)
    break_conditions:
      - treats biological fitness as equivalent to ethical correctness
      - imports competitive selection framing — doctrine does not "compete" for survival
      - assumes replication fidelity as an absolute good (rigid systems fail under novel conditions)
      - uses evolutionary language to justify doctrine changes without Mirror review
    example: >
      Pantheon propagation alternates between stabilization phases (exact replication
      of canonical nodes into new operator instances) and innovation phases
      (cross-domain transfer generating draft nodes for canon review).
      The Mirror gate acts as selection pressure.
    confidence: 0.70
    status: draft
    version: "0.1"
    notes: >
      Draft status pending canon review. The analogy is productive but the break
      conditions are numerous. Biological metaphors carry high anthropomorphic drift risk.
